Ahala, Maelium: Servilius Ahala, master of the horse under the dictator Cincinnatus, was sent in the year 439 lae. to arrest Spurius Maelius, who was suspected of aiming at regal power. Maelius refused to obey the summons of the dictator, and was accordingly slain on the spot. It is, however, by no means certain that the suspicions against Maelius were well founded. By distributing grain among the poorer classes at a time of great scarcity, he made himself the idol of the Plebeians, butan object of hatred and suspicion to the Patricians. Itis, accordrhgly, impossible to say whether he fell as a traitor to his country, or as a martyr to his own generosity. Cicero, doubtless, believed him guilty.
